english:
  title: A Blessing for Duke Choi Yu-eom, Commander of the Capital Guard and Minister of State
  author: Seok Mu-oe
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Ten Bodies of the Buddha move freely everywhere—in every thought, the Way answers with radiance. The great matter of causality admits no end, yet with each phrase the path of practice seems to break. Still, we may plant trees in empty space and coax lotus blossoms to bloom in fire. Thus I pour forth the fullness of my sincere heart, hoping for the profound aid of heaven's mysteries.

    Though I am old and beset by illness, my virtue and conduct both fail—yet I reflect that our Lord of Pure River is truly the great patron of White Lotus Temple. His ancestor chanted the Lotus Sutra and vowed to protect the Dharma; his father, a master of eloquent words, composed the inscription founding this sacred place. Because the karmic bonds of his forebears run so deep in this teaching, the faith of his descendants flourishes manifold beyond that of others. How much more so now, when his lordship's actions arise in this difficult age, bringing thunder and rain to a single region, wielding grace and authority on heaven's behalf, building an unshakeable refuge for our humble temple! The whole assembly rejoices; light breaks forth from every valley.

    My own sense of reverence and gratitude—how can mere words contain it? For three days I now prepare this incense-gathering, offering these small devotions to all the directions, trusting that these true merits may reach the Buddha's wisdom. I humbly pray: may the roots of misfortune wither away, may the vines of blessing flourish abundantly in the Purple Palace; may the bones of his years grow luminous and eternal, his face like flowers unfading in the halls of highest office.
  footnotes:
    - The Ten Bodies (十身) refer to the multiple manifestations of the Buddha in Buddhist philosophy.
    - The great matter of causality (一大事因緣) is a key concept from the Lotus Sutra concerning enlightenment.
    - White Lotus Temple (白蓮寺) is the specific temple for which this blessing is composed.
    - The Purple Palace (紫樞) is a poetic reference to the imperial court; the Yellow Hall (黃閣) refers to the office of the prime minister.
    - This is a dedicatory prayer composed by the Buddhist monk to bless the lineage and continued prosperity of a high-ranking official and temple patron.
